	<div id="id2476" class="post">
		<h2 class="title"><span class="image-wrapper"><img height="47" alt="Smile: Databinder's got forums" width="490" class="title" src="../../../resources/net.databinder.components.RenderedLabel/e30d149f"/><span class="title">Smile: Databinder&#039;s got forums</span></span></h2>
		<div class="byline"><span>
			<span>By <span class="alias">n8han</span>, <span>on March 30, 2006</span></span>
			<span id="id2477" class="tags">
					{&nbsp;<span><a href="../../../code/tag/databinder/#selected-tag"><span>databinder</span></a><span id="id2478">, </span></span><span><a href="../../../code/tag/spam/#selected-tag"><span>spam</span></a></span>&nbsp;}
			</span>
		</span></div>
		<div><p class="out"><img src="/pictures/emote.png" alt="" /></p>


	<p>Those of you feeling the need to grin, blush, roll your eyes, or make that scary devil-face in response to Databinder—now you have <a href="http://databinder.net/forum">a forum to emote in</a>. (The forum is also good for technical questions.)</p>


	<p>People had asked for a mailing list, and I had already <em>sudo apt-get install mailman</em>‘d when I thought, “Why a mailing list? Don’t people get enough e-mail?”</p>


	<p>I decided forums are better for new users (sound familiar?). You can more easily browse topics with them, and get involved without committing to frequent e-mails.</p>


	<p>For now you can post without registering, but when “Opportunity for Partnership” spams start showing up, that short-cut will have to go.</p>


	<p>Compliment of the season!</p></div>
